Accor, BP, Danone, National Grid, Total: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   S t e p h e n   K l e e g e
-- 
2011-08-03T04:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-02/accor-bp-danone-national-grid-total-europe-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index fell 1.9 percent to 256.98. The
Stoxx 50 Index dropped 1.6 percent to 2,447.51. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark measure for nations using the euro,
decreased 1.9 percent to 2,544.89.  Accor SA (AC)  : The French hotel company signed a
contract to sell caterer Lenotre to Sodexo and said it expects
to complete the sale by the end of September. The shares slid
3.8 percent to 28.82 euros.  BP Plc (BP/)  : Europe’s second-biggest oil company is
carrying out repairs to a crude unit at the Whiting refinery in
Indiana that may last seven to 10 days, according to two people
familiar with the plant’s operations. The shares fell 2.4
percent to 447.05 pence.  Casino Guichard-Perrachon SA (CO)  : The supermarket
chain, which shares the control of Cia. Brasileira de
Distribuicao Grupo Pao de Acucar with the Diniz family, filed a
complaint against Pao de Acucar to  Brazil ’s securities
regulator, according to its website. The shares slid 2.3 percent
to 60.23 euros.  Credit Agricole SA (ACA)  : Credit Agricole Leasing &
Factoring agreed to sell its Eurofactor U.K. unit to  GE Capital ,
the French bank said in an e-mailed statement. It didn’t give
financial terms. The shares fell 3.5 percent to 8 euros.  Danone (BN)  SA: The yogurt maker signed an accord to buy
Wockhardt Group’s nutrition business in  India  for about 250
million euros ($355 million). The shares rose 0.7 percent to
49.51 euros.  National Grid Plc (NG/)  : The operator of the U.K.’s
power and natural gas networks has signed an agreement with
Iberdrola SA’s Scottish Power to reduce output at its 2,400-
megawatt Longannet electricity station until October while work
is carried out on the electricity network. The shares rose 2
percent to 602.5 pence.  Total SA (FP)  :  France ’s biggest oil company’s chief
executive officer, Christophe de Margerie, will face trial
related to the Iraqi Oil-for-Food program, Europe 1 radio
reported, citing a judicial source. A Total spokesperson
couldn’t be reached for comment. Shares slid 0.7 percent to
36.80 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Kleege in New York at 
 skleege@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net  